properties.name: The village of Guendel, Rufisque (now a suburb of Dakar), Sénégal (West Africa), c. 1905 (7804097800)
properties.discription:
From a 1905 postcard.

 Raymond Mauny published a collection of early mentions of Rufisque in Notes Africaines  (Number 46, April, 1950, pp. 47-49).  Among them is this one from about 350 years ago:  "Rufisque compte alors environ 200 cases, et est peuplée de 300 hommes plus les femmes et les enfants.  Les gens vont presque nus.  On y voit des Catholiques (les Portugais entre autres, qui y sont nombreux), les circoncis qui approchent du Judaïsme ["Par d'autres textes... on sait qu'il s'agit ici de griots."], des Mahométans et des Idolâtres.  Ils vivent de riz, de mil et de maïs, mangent peu de viande mais beaucoup do poisson.  Les hommes y sont bien faits et les femmes de petite vertu.  Tous parlent un portugais corrompu."

"On tire du pays des cuirs, de la gomme, des plumes, de l'ivoire, de l'ambre gris, de l'indigo, de la civette, et de grosses toiles de coton rayées de bleu et blanc, que l'on revend a la Côte de l'Or."

properties.name: OldestAustrianPictPostcard
properties.discription: English:  Oldest known Austrian-Hungarian picture postcard, sent from Vienna to Zombor (Sombor) and back to Vienna; date sent: May, 19th 1871. The card was sent out by the Serb Petar Manojlović to his cousin. Postcard is written in Serbian language with Cyrillic script.Српски / srpski:  Najstarija poznata razglednica u Austro-Ugarskoj, poslata iz Beča u Sombor, pa vraćena u Beč (datum slanja: 19. maj 1871. godine). Razglednicu je poslao Srbin Petar Manojlović svome rođaku. Napisana je na srpskom jeziku ćiriličnim pismom.Deutsch:  Älteste bekannte österreichische Ansichtskarte, versendet am 19. Mai 1871 als Einschreiben (Reko) von Wien nach Zombor und zurück nach Wien. Die Karte wurde von dem Serben Petar Manojlovic an seinen Vetter verschickt. Offiziell wurden Ansichtskarten in Österreich-Ungarn erst ab 1. Januar 1885 zugelassen.

properties.name: Vojvoda Micko Krstić with companions
properties.discription:
English:  Voivode Micko KrstićСрпски / srpski:  Micko Krstić, četnički vojvoda: Robijao 17 godina, pomilovanje odbio rečima - ja nisam Bugarin
Rođen je i poginuo u Makedoniji. Poreklom je iz okoline Ohrida. Još u mladosti je četovao protiv Turaka i Arnauta. Zatim se borio protiv Bugara koji nisu imali prolaz u njegovom Poreču. Turci su ga uhvatili na prevaru i osudili na doživotnu tamnicu. Robijao je 17 godina. Pomilovan je kao Bugarin i odbio pomilovanje rečima: "Ja nisam Bugarin". Posle dve i po godine je pomilovan - ali kao Srbin.
Vojvoda Micko sa svojim četnicima: U poznim godinama živeo je u Kragujevcu, gde se oko njega stvorio najjači četnički centar.
Mali Vojin zvani Ture, upijao je njegove priče.
Voja Ture, ući će u istoriju četništva kao Vojvoda Vuk
Odmah je otišao u četničku majku - goru. Stvorio je četu i zarobio čuvenog bugarskog vojvodu Damnjana Grujeva i poklonio mu život.

Kada su stigle mlade četničke snage Gligor Sokolović, vojvoda Babunski i Dovezenski, vojvoda Micko je kao star čovek otišao na odmor u Srbiju. Živeo je tri godine u Kragujevcu i Požarevcu. Vratio se u Makedoniju. Ubili su ga Turci između Kičeva i Broda.

properties.name: USSR 1931-07-25 Graf Zeppelin
properties.discription:
English:  USSR 1931-07-25 Graf Zeppelin postcard, from the third stage of its flight. 
Graf Zeppelin’s Arctic Flight in 1931 was both a scientific expedition and a dramatic display of the airship’s ability under extreme conditions. In July, 1931, the ship carried a team of scientists from Germany, the United States, the Soviet Union, and Sweden on an exploration of the Arctic
First Stage: Friedrichshafen-Berlin. The journey began on Friday, July 24, 1931, with an 8 hour-7 minute flight from Friedrichshafen to Berlin-Staaken airfield.
Second Stage: Berlin-Leningrad. LZ-127 departed Berlin-Staaken in the early hours of July 25, and passed over Sweden, Estonia, and Finland before landing that evening in Leningrad.
Third Stage: Leningrad to Franz-Josef Land and rendezvous with icebreaker Malygin. On Sunday, July 26, Graf Zeppelin left Leningrad to began its voyage north. Around 7:00 PM in the evening the ship crossed the Arctic Circle, flying over the White Sea between the peninsulas of Kola and Kanin. Late afternoon July 27 1931, LZ-127 reached Hooker Island in Franz-Josef Land and landed on the water to exchange sacks of mail with the Soviet icebreaker Malygin, which was on a tourist cruise to the Arctic.  As with other Graf Zeppelin flights, the polar expedition was largely financed with revenue from stamp collectors. Graf Zeppelin transferred about 650 pounds of mail to the Malygin, and picked up about 270 pounds of mail from the Soviet ship in return; about 50,000 pieces of philatelic mail in total were carried on the flight (as was this postcard).

Mail dropped at the Malygin received an anchor shaped transit cancel from the ship 'BRISE-GLACE "MALYGUIN" - ARCTIQUE - 27VII31'. Mail was delivered to passengers or transported via icebreaker or dogsled back to land, where it was then forwarded to addressees around the world.

properties.name: Открытка самодельная армейская 1980е
properties.discription:
English:  Soviet Army hand-made postcard, 1987.
Due to lack of colorful postcards, particularly in the Soviet Army units in Afghanistan (of course, there were plenty standard so called 'army' covers without any pictures and stamps of 0.5 и 1 kopecks value), the soldiers made postcards themselves. They took a colorful poster or wall-paper on thick paper, cut out 'postcards' and drew address lines and post code boxes on the reverse side. No stamps were required for sending soldiers' mail, and all such hand-made postcards reached the addressees successfully.
This unused postcard is drawn in hard pencil on reverse side of embossed paper. The postcard has a colorful drawing on its other side.
Русский:  Открытка самодельная армейская. 
В условиях постоянного дефицита, особенно в Афганистане, в Советской Армии красочных открыток (в избытке были только т.н. "армейские" конверты без рисунков и марок по 0,5 и 1 копейке) для отправки домой, открытки делали сами: брали красочный плакат либо красивые обои на плотной бумаге, вырезали из них "открытки" и рисовали на обратной стороне графы для письма (слева), индекса (слева внизу), адреса туда (справа вверху) и адреса обратного (справа внизу). Открытки военнослужащих срочной службы пересылались бесплатно (марка не требовалась), и все такие "самоделки" доходили до адресатов.
Данная неотправленная открытка разграфлена твёрдым карандашом на обратной стороне тиснёной бумаги. На обратной стороне красочный рисунок.

properties.name: Ingenjörkasernen, Karlskrona (01)
properties.discription: Svenska:  Ingenjörkasernen vid Blåportsgatan i Karlskrona. Byggnaden uppfördes 1907 som kasern för fästningsingenjörkompaniet Göta ingenjörkår (Ing 2) som fanns i Karlskrona åren 1908–1937. Under perioden 1940–1943 användes kasernen som förläggning till inkallade beredskapsförband. Åren 1943–1990 som stabsbyggnad till Blekinge kustartilleriförsvar (BK). Kasernen har en tvillingkasern i Vaxholm, som är identisk med den i Karlskrona.

properties.name: Seglingsberg flygfoto 1933
properties.discription:
English:  Aerial picture postcard of Seglingsberg, near Ramnäs, Sweden 1933. The wide water is the river Kolbäcksån, the narrow with a sluice behind the trees is Strömsholms canal. The white mound originates from the Seglingsberg blast furnace which closed 1907. The card was posted in 1938.
Svenska:  Flygfoto vykort över Seglingsberg, strax norr om Ramnäs 1933. Det breda vattenpartiet är Kolbäcksån och det smala är Strömsholms kanal. Slussen bakom träden är döpt till Hertig Karl av Södermanland. Den stora vita slagghögen är lämningar efter hyttan. Hyttan stängdes ca 1907. Vykortet är postgånget 1938.

properties.discription:

Abgestempelt am 22. Juli 1890 in der Schweizer Gemeinde Gsteig im Amtsbezirk Saanen.

properties.name: THELEMANN, Otto Heinrich - Postkarte r (1890-07-22)
properties.discription:
Deutsch:  Postkarte (Rückseite) seines Bruders Ernst an den damaligen Pastor der ev. Kirche in Wüsten, Otto Heinrich Thelemann. Abgestempelt am 22. Juli 1890 in der Schweizer Gemeinde Gsteig im Amtsbezirk Saanen.

Sehr geehrter!
Herrn Pastor H. Thelemann
????
Wüsten b/Salzuflen
Lippe
Deutschland


0000Gsteig b/Saanen, 21. Juli 1890
0000Berner Oberland
000000Entschuldige die lakonische Kürze!
000000Es ist schon 10 Uhr., Post von hier morgen früh 6 Uhr!
????!
Lieber Heinrich.
Zu Deinem Geburtstage wünsche ich Dir nochmal herzlichst
Glück u. Segen. – Ich will hier keinen längeren Geburtstags-
Brief schreiben – den habe ich schon vor einem Monat geschrieben.
Ich will die aber von meiner Reise etwas erzählen. Sonnabend d. 19.
brach ich um 9 Uhr morgens mit einem ???? u. ging quer durch den Jura
über Arlesheim etc. Büsserach, Mervelier, Vermes auf den Weissen-
stein, wo wir um 7 Uhr abends ankamen. Hier konnten wir auch sagen:
Grosse Steine, kleine Steine, müde Beine – Aussicht keine! Trostloser
Nebel lagerte auf der Spitze des Berges, von dem man sch prächtige
Aussicht auf das Berner Oberland haben sollte. Wir gingen dann auch
sogleich herunter, kamen um 9 Uhr in Solothurn an, wo wir bei einem
???? u. ???? übernachteten. Nach der Tour von 4 Uhr morgens –
9 Uhr abends, habe ich geschlafen, wie ein Bär. Am anderen Morgen um ½ 8 Uhr
aus dem Bette, Solothurn angesehen, dann 2 Stunden bis Utzenstorf ge-
gangen. Von hier mit der Bahn über Bern, wo me. ????  in den Zug ein-
stieg, über Thun, Scherzligen, Thuner See nach Spiez, wo wir um 3 Uhr waren.
Von da zu Fuss 5 Stunden durch das Simmetal nach Weissenburg, in
dessen Nähe wir à 60 cts. übernachteten. Am anderen Morgen um 8 Uhr weiter
durch Zweisimmen, Saanen, Gstaad nach Gsteig, wo uns unser Groß-
vater: Lbb. ???? Lbb. eingeladen hatte. Hier um 7 Uhr abds angekommen.
Hier werden wir wohl 4-5 Tage blieben um dann über Adelboden, wohin
uns „Phil. ???? Balz (????) eingeladen, nach Frutigen u. Spiez, wo ich
dann nach Bern gehe, um Pf. ???? zu besuchen. Dann Heimkehr nach
Hause. Mit herzlichen Grüssen, nochmals herzl. Glück= und Segenswünschen.

000000000000Dein treuer Bruder00Ernst.

properties.name: Lomé Togo Weg nach dem Gouverneurspalast 1904
properties.discription: Lomé, weg nach dem Gouverneurspalast. � L�allée menant au Palais du gouverneur. Le gouverneur August Kohler (1858 � 1902), qui était arrivé au Togo en 1895, décide de construire le Palais et en choisit l�emplacement, à 250 mètres de la plage. La ville de Lomé compte alors 2084 habitants, dont 31 Européens. La construction, entreprise sans plan ni financement dès 1897, s�interrompt et reprend plusieurs fois, pour s�achever entre1905 et 1906 sous la direction de E. Schmidt, le premier architecte employé par l�administration coloniale allemande. Pour que l�ensemble de l�édifice puisse être vu depuis les navires en mer, et ce malgré un talus qui bordait le rivage, le bâtiment reçu un soubassement de 3,50 m. Sur la façade est, débouche deux avenues, Franz-Fredrichstrasse et Wilelmstrasse, l�actuelle avenue A. Sarraut qui va parallèle à la plage. La façade sud est tournée vers la mer. A la même époque, quelques maisons d�habitation, destinées aux fonctionnaires, sont construites aux abords immédiats du Palais. � Cette carte postale, dont le verso n�est pas divisé pour séparer l�adresse de la correspondance comme cela fut recommandé par l�Union postale à partir de 1904, doit dater de cette année, soit avant l�achèvement du Palais.

properties.name: A Scrap of Paper (17603992861)
properties.discription: This is a postcard published by the Valentine Company and it was one of a number published along the same lines. Shortly after the outbreak of the First World War, Mr Bonar Law who was leader of the Conservative Party, said at a meeting at the Guildhall in the City of London, "The 4th of August 1914 is an outstanding date in history; the date on which Great Britain declared war on Germany." He went on to say, that Britain's ambassador to Berlin, Sir Edward Goschen had called on the German Chancellor, Theobald von Bethmann-Hollweg and found him in a state of great excitement because Britain had declared war on Germany and "Just for a scrap of paper". Needless to say that his remark did not go down very well in Britain. The “Scrap of Paper” was the 1839 Treaty of London in which Britain, France, Austria, Russia and Prussia had guaranteed the existence, Sovereignty and neutrality of Belgium. The image of the document with the seals and signatures had been used by the Parliamentary Recruiting Committee in recruiting posters and leaflets and the postcard publishers acknowledged their permission to use the image on the reverse of the postcard.

It shows the railway as it was when built, a scene that is still very recognisable, although somewhat different, today.

properties.name: St Helens 292 NTC 109G (4559735749)
properties.discription:
PIKE POSTCARD by W. G. S. Hyde
This AEC Swift carries an Alexander  B43D body, it was purchased second hand by St Helens, in 1973, having been new to Lancashire United in 1969.

The Transport Act of 1968 had allowed for the creation of Passenger Transport Executives, Merseyside PTE being one of the first so designated. St. Helens lay outside the PTE catchment although some of its operational areas, such as Prescot, fell within the PTE's jurisdiction. The Local Government Act of 1972 created the new Merseyside County, which included the boroughs of St. Helens and Southport. As a result, on the 1st April 1974, the transport undertakings of these two municipal undertakings were absorbed into the Merseyside PTE, and at midnight on the 31st March 1974, St. Helens Corporation Transport passed into history.

properties.name: Postcard Album
properties.discription: English:  Album for a postcard collection from the "Golden Age" of American postcards. The album model is "The Ideal", and it was made by the J.L. Hanson Co., Chicago. It dates from the early 1910s. The lower photo shows two ways the postcards can be held by the album pages. No label or room for a label is needed, as the American postcards of the time nearly always had a caption printed on the front, as shown here.

properties.name: Treadles Tea Room Postcard - Northbrook (15208219608)
properties.discription:
English:  The annual tea for the Cloyne UCW was held at the Treadles Tea Room in Northbrook.
Treadles consisted of a church with a large addition. In the top left photo the original church was the section on the left with the new addition on the right. John and Doreen Howard started this enterprise.  The tea room was not the only attraction as John and Doreen refurbished and sold antiques and tole painting supplies. Tole painting classes were also given by Doreen.

properties.name: Rosh Hashana Montevideo 1932
properties.discription:
English:  Shanah Tovah, greeting card, Montevideo 1931-1932. Inscribed in Hebrew characters: "LeShanah Tovah Tikatevu" (traditional Hebrew greeting for Rosh Hashanah: "For a good year may you be inscribed [in the book of life]") and "Montevideo" (in Yiddish orthography), followed by התרצב (the Hebrew calendar notation for the year 5692).
Español:  Cartís brajá o tarjeta de salutación para Rosh Hashaná (Año Nuevo Judío), Montevideo, 1932. Incripción en caracteres hebreos: LeShaná Tová Tikatevu (idioma hebreo: "Para un buen año sean [ustedes] inscriptos [en el libro de la vida]"); Montevideo (en ortografia ídish) seguido por el año 5692 (expresado en caracteres hebreos).

properties.name: Perim Hotel and Club
properties.discription: English:  The Perim Hotel, the only hotel Perim ever had during the British period, was initially called the Grand Hotel when it was built before 1888, then The Oriental, and finally The Perim Hotel. Perim's cricket grounds were next to the hotel and most of the people shown on this picture from circa 1910 are probably cricket players. Accommodations tended to be very basic on Perim Island, where all activities centered on coaling operations until 1936. The hotel belonged to the Perim Coal Company. Contemporary real photo postcard.
